title: Led Zeppelin 1969.01.10 - San Francisco
description:
This week&#039;s selection is San Francisco, 1-10-1969, the Fillmore West.  2ndGen>DAT>CDR>FLAC[8] - a good audience source.  We&#039;re moving on from Gonzaga at this point, eleven days later, with a similar but different setlist, with HMMT and White Summer reversed, and the addition of four more tracks (in 11 days!) mostly from the first album.  

This show contains a curiosity that some of you (like myself) will find fascinating.  This is possibly the last time (and the only time that I can find) that Led Zeppelin plays "For Your Love."  Robert introduces the song, to great applause, as "something from the time of, uhm, Keith Relf" and Jimmy takes off on a totally deconstructed, psychedelic version of the song that made Eric Clapton quit the band.  I don&#039;t want to ruin it for you.  But this show is worth the download for this track alone.  The guys use it to close the show, and it&#039;s devastating.

This is a tremendous early show, with Zeppelin playing their brains out and a pretty good recording besides - it shows its age, but we *are* talking about 1969 here - this is one of the shows that I wondered about when the thing came up about Bill Graham&#039;s tapes a while back.  If Graham had a soundboard of this show, I&#039;d give my left pinkie to get it.

Led Zeppelin
January 10th, 1969
Fillmore West - San Francisco, CA

2ndGen>DAT>CDR
